{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8cbc29b3-8389-468d-b28a-8ad460c58a63","content":"On macOS, if `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT since it's not bundled), you can recover a crash dump using the OS-level facilities:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** – run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n2. **Check macOS crash reports** – look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.ips` or `.crash` files generated automatically by ReportCrash.\n3. **Convert to a usable dump** – use `lldb` to open the core file:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   macOS writes cores to `/cores/` (if enabled via `ulimit`).\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, you may also need:\n   ```\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** – once loaded, use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc. to inspect the crash.\n\n**Key notes:**\n- macOS SIP (System Integrity Protection) can prevent core dumps for some paths. Ensure your app runs from a writable, non-SIP-protected location.\n- For richer .NET diagnostics, set `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` — though these rely on `createdump` being present.\n- NativeAOT apps embed limited managed metadata, so `lldb` may only show native frames unless you also have the `.dsym` / debug symbols available.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a5209c23-e45f-4de0-bf23-3e7cb84d546c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about recovering crash dumps on macOS for NativeAOT apps when `createdump` is not available. This seems like a general knowledge question about .NET NativeAOT debugging on macOS. Let me check if there's any relevant documentation in the current repository first.","outputTokens":474,"requestId":"6014:2CF44:D77F1D:FB4557:69EACB3E"},"id":"d9cad6d1-8894-449e-bb86-7dcad101d495","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:45:47.777Z","parentId":"cc700faa-0be8-437c-b306-71daf157eb24"}
